## 4.3 Portfolio and Risk Management

### Purpose

Extend price impact from trade-level execution to portfolio-level risk, accounting P&L, liquidity reports, and fire-sale stress tests.

### Setup / formulation

The accounting P&L $X_t$ and fundamental P&L $Y_t$ differ because observed prices include price impact.

Define the internal trading footprint:

$$
F_t = I_t Q_t.
$$

Define the external trading footprint:

$$
\bar{F}_t = -\bar{\alpha}_t Q_t.
$$

Then:

$$
X_t - Y_t = F_t + \bar{F}_t.
$$

Here:

- $F_t$ is the mark-to-market distortion due to the trader’s own impact,
- $\bar{F}_t$ is the mark-to-market distortion due to external market impact.

### Main result

Accounting P&L can be biased by both internal and external impact. A portfolio’s apparent value may differ materially from its liquidation-adjusted value.

### Interpretation

Portfolio managers and risk managers should monitor not only current mark-to-market P&L but also:

- how much of that P&L is footprint,
- how expensive it would be to close the position,
- and how vulnerable the position is to external crowding or fire sales.

