## 4.3.1 How Price Impact Distorts Accounting P&L and Perceived Risk

### Purpose

Formalize the difference between accounting P&L and fundamental or liquidation-adjusted P&L.

### Setup / formulation

Accounting P&L marks the portfolio to observed prices. Fundamental P&L marks the portfolio to unperturbed prices.

The difference is the trading footprint:

$$
X_t-Y_t = F_t+\bar{F}_t.
$$

Ignoring external impact for simplicity:

$$
X_t - Y_t = I_t Q_t.
$$

If $Q_T=0$, then:

$$
X_T=Y_T.
$$

### Main result

Mark-to-market accounting can overstate or understate realizable portfolio value when price impact is present.

### Interpretation

A portfolio may appear profitable because its own buying pressure moved prices upward. But liquidation removes the position and forces the impact to be paid back.

The relevant economic question is not only:

> What is the current accounting P&L?

but also:

> What P&L remains after closing the position under a realistic impact model?

