## 4.3.1.1 Expected Closing P&L

### Purpose

Define expected closing P&L and connect it to current accounting P&L, footprint, alpha, and future transaction costs.

### Setup / formulation

Let $\tau$ be a stopping time representing the time at which the portfolio is closed.

If the portfolio is fully closed at $\tau$, then:

$$
Q_\tau=0
\quad\Rightarrow\quad
X_\tau=Y_\tau.
$$

Starting from time $t$, expected closing P&L adjusts current accounting P&L by removing footprint and subtracting expected future execution costs.

A schematic form is:

$$
\mathbb{E}[X_\tau\mid\mathcal{F}_t]
=
X_t
-
\text{current footprint}
+
\text{expected future alpha}
-
\text{expected future transaction costs}.
$$

In simplified cases with no future alpha and a quadratic liquidation-cost approximation,

$$
\mathbb{E}[X_\tau\mid\mathcal{F}_t]
\approx
Y_t
-
\frac{\Lambda}{2}Q_t^2.
$$

### Main result

Expected closing P&L is the relevant valuation metric for liquidation risk. It is not generally equal to accounting P&L.

### Interpretation

A large profitable-looking portfolio may have poor expected closing P&L if:

- its mark-to-market value is inflated by its own impact,
- its liquidation cost is large,
- or external market pressure is expected to move against it.

