## 4.3.1.2 P&L Bias Examples

### Purpose

Use round-trip examples to show how price impact biases perceived performance.

### Setup / formulation

Consider a round trip with three phases:

- leverage into a position,
- hold the position,
- deleverage out of the position.

Under the OW model, for a trade of size $Q$, expected fundamental P&L is:

$$
\mathbb{E}[Y_T]
=
-\frac{\lambda}{2+\beta T}Q^2.
$$

Expected accounting P&L is:

$$
\mathbb{E}[X_T]
=
\frac{2\lambda}{2+\beta T}Q_0Q
-
\mathbb{E}[Y_T].
$$

### Main result

Entering a position can create positive mark-to-market P&L even though the fundamental P&L is negative.

Exiting a position removes the inflated mark-to-market value and realizes the cost.

### Interpretation

A trader should not interpret footprint-driven accounting gains as alpha. If a strategy appears profitable only while increasing positions, but loses when closing them, the apparent profit is caused by impact and not by genuine prediction.

